info.title: Events Events
info.x-hubspot-api-use-case: You want to view a timeline of the interactions that a contact has had with your content. You can then use this timeline to build a dataset for custom analytics or present a contact timeline in an external application.
info.x-hubspot-introduction: Use the web analytics API to fetch events associated with CRM records of any type. This includes standard events, such as website page views and email opens, as well as custom events.

get.description: Retrieve instances of event completion data. For example, retrieve all event completions associated with a specific contact.

parameters.name: objectType
parameters.description: The type of CRM object to filter event instances on (e.g., `contact`). To retrieve event data for a specific CRM record, include the additional `objectId` query parameter (below).

parameters.name: eventType
parameters.description: The event type name. You can retrieve available event types using the [event types endpoint](#get-%2Fevents%2Fv3%2Fevents%2Fevent-types).

parameters.name: after
parameters.description: The paging cursor token of the last successfully read resource will be returned as the `paging.next.after` JSON property of a paged response containing more results.

parameters.name: limit
parameters.description: The maximum number of results to display per page.

parameters.name: sort
parameters.description: Sort direction based on the timestamp of the event instance, `ASCENDING` or `DESCENDING`.

parameters.name: occurredAfter
parameters.description: Filter for event data that occurred after a specific datetime.

parameters.name: occurredBefore
parameters.description: Filter for event data that occurred before a specific datetime.

parameters.name: objectId
parameters.description: The ID of the CRM Object to filter event instances on. When including this parameter, you must also include the `objectType` parameter.

parameters.name: objectProperty.{propname}
parameters.description: Instead of retrieving event data for a specific object by its ID, you can specify a unique identifier property. For contacts, you can use the `email` property. (e.g., `objectProperty.email=name@domain.com`).

parameters.name: property.{propname}
parameters.description: Filter for event completions that contain a specific value for an event property (e.g., `property.hs_city=portland`). For properties values with spaces, replaces spaces with `%20` or `+` (e.g., `property.hs_city=new+york`).

parameters.name: id
parameters.description: ID of an event instance. IDs are 1:1 with event instances. If you provide this filter and additional filters, the other filters must match the values on the event instance to yield results.

link.description: A URL that can be used to retrieve the next page results.

after.description: A paging cursor token for retrieving subsequent pages.

next.description: Specifies the paging information needed to retrieve the next set of results in a paginated API response

before.description: A paging cursor token for retrieving previous pages.

link.description: A URL that can be used to retrieve the previous pages' results.

prev.description: specifies the paging information needed to retrieve the previous set of results in a paginated API response

occurredAt.description: An ISO 8601 timestamp when the event occurred.

eventType.description: The format of the `eventType` string is `ae{appId}_{eventTypeLabel}`, `pe{portalId}_{eventTypeLabel}`, or just `e_{eventTypeLabel}` for HubSpot events.

id.description: A unique identifier for the event.

objectId.description: The objectId of the object which did the event.

properties.description: A key-value map of event-specific properties. The available properties depend on the event type definition.

objectType.description: The objectType for the object which did the event.

get.description:
This endpoint returns a list of event type names which are visible to you. You may use these event type names to query the API for specific event instances of a desired type.

Note: the `get_types` method is only supported in the Python SDK version `12.0.0-beta.1` or later.

parameters.name: searchString
parameters.description: Characters in the event name that the user is searching for. This search is a naive “contains” search, no fuzzy matching is done.

parameters.name: after
parameters.description: The paging cursor token of the last successfully read resource will be returned as the `paging.next.after` JSON property of a paged response containing more results.

parameters.name: limit
parameters.description: The maximum number of results to display per page.

link.description: A URL that can be used to retrieve the next page results.

after.description: A paging cursor token for retrieving subsequent pages.

next.description: Specifies the paging information needed to retrieve the next set of results in a paginated API response

post.summary: Send a batch of event completions
post.description: Send multiple event completions at once.

occurredAt.description: The time when this event occurred. If this isn't set, the current time will be used.

eventName.description: The internal name of the event (`pe<portalID>_eventName`). Can be retrieved through the [event definitions API](https://developers.hubspot.com/docs/reference/api/analytics-and-events/custom-events/custom-event-definitions#get-%2Fevents%2Fv3%2Fevent-definitions) or in [HubSpot's UI](https://knowledge.hubspot.com/reports/create-custom-behavioral-events-with-the-code-wizard#find-internal-name).

utk.description: The visitor's usertoken. Used for associating the event data with a CRM record.

uuid.description: Include a universally unique identifier to assign a unique ID to the event completion. Can be useful for matching data between HubSpot and other external systems.

email.description: The visitor's email address. Used for associating the event data with a CRM record.

properties.description: The event properties to update. Takes the format of key-value pairs (property internal name and property value).
